< Text>
We organized a birthday party today. In the first place, we booked party hall. The hall had an option for projector. But when we turned up today for party, there was another party going on in the party hall. When we asked about our party, the manager who was in charge offered main restaurant hall for party. As we had invited guests and everything was set, we didn't want to create an issue there. The real chaos started when they started serving food.  In fact the hall was fine, even though projector wasn't available. There were no starters after first 10 guest serving. Post that, there were no plates, spoons, forks for long time. Guest had to wait for at least 15 min before they got the plates and spoons. After that, most of the main course dishes were over and they were not refilling it. Because of this chaos, we wanted to see the owner who took the booking, but he wasn't present nor reachable. On our insistence during settlement, when owner turned up, he said "pay the money or else I'll call 911", when we just wanted to talk about party hall, projector options, insufficient food, lack of plates and silverware. We barely expected an apology for the chaos. Instead he was very very rude!!!

We paid the money and came back as we knew he doesn't deserve any good talk, as he talked like thug!!!!

All the best for his business! I feel bad for his employees.

< review>
Celebrations is the hotspot for parties! The banquet room is spacious and I had a blast dancing to the awesome party music. The waiters were on their feet... replenishing the buffet food promptly and taking away our plates. They were also accommodating in permitting us to use the projector and karaoke systems. <Review>I went here for a party and I have been to numerous restaurants in bay area and all over US and not even once I experienced such a horrible service, horrible food and a rude, arrogant owner and clueless manager all at once. I am not able to understand why this owner is in the restaurant business if all he knows is to call his customers thieves and threaten to call 911 when we tried to complain about the fact that most of the people in the party did not get any food.

All the curries, lamb and chicken had just the gravy and no meat in them for most of the time. I could see guest just taking the sauce without any meat after waiting for long time and checking multiple times. And when they filled some curries there were no nan or rice to go with it. And after sometime there were no plates, cutlery or desert bowls and glass for drinking water.

I could literally see each one of the guests going to the restaurant staff and asking them to get food or plates or cutlery or water. The supposed manager of the restaurant went missing during the party and showed up after most of the guests left the place. My friend who hosted the party was insulted by the owner when we complained to him about the service. He got the number of guests from the staff and told us you have complained enough to the staff and this is your bill, just pay and go or else this is going to end very badly for you and I am calling 911.

But in this case the restaurant and the owner were there not to help but simply make it a horrible experience for everybody. But what I am unable to comprehend is why folks like this restaurant  owner is in the restaurant business if they don't understand the basics of restaurant business like treating your guests with minimum courtesy and provide them decent food. < text>
Solid lunch buffet.  A little on the pricey side, but they have chai, naan, a selection of desserts, and a good mix of veggie and meat options. < text>
My husband and daughter came for lunch buffet today at Celebrations Indian Cuisine and we were pleasantly surprised by the quality of food, service, and ambiance. We have been travelling a lot recently for business and wanted to have some good food, especially my husband was craving for delicious food.

Our favorite was Lamb Vindaloo, Chicken 65, and Butter Chicken. My husband liked the Goat Masala although it was a bit spicy for me.

We spent nearly one hour eating at the restaurant and were very full while leaving. The servers helped us choose the dessert, we went for Gulab Jamun, they were kind enough to explain to us what it means.

The coke machine was not working, but they arranged to give us other beverages. Beverages here are free included in the buffet, so is Mango Lassi.

We were served hot breads on the table, I requested Garlic Naan and they were very good. We ate a lot of Garlic Naans.

Overall, it was a very satisfying experience for us. If and when we visit the  San Francisco Bay Area again, we will surely visit this restaurant again.< /text>

<Date>1469812311066< /Date><rating>5<//rating><review>We celebrated birthday party for our office colleague yesterday at Celebrations, everything was near perfect. Our group of 20 people were all seated together in a nice private setting, two servers at our table all the time. We ordered several appetizers, but the best of the pick was Chicken Tikka Kabab, and Paneer Tikka - delicious, flavorful, and delicately cooked. Dinner was ready on time and the waiters were ready to serve, but we requested more time for socializing and cutting our birthday cake. Finally, when we were ready for dinner, the dishes were all amazing ! If you haven't tried their Shahi Paneer, I recommend you do so. The Butter Chicken had soft, tender chicken pieces cooked in grill. All in all, a very pleasant experience for our group. We are coming again in 3 weeks for another party - farewell to one of our long serving employee. Overall, we spent nearly 3 hours at Celebrations, they can get busy at times with big groups.

Highly recommended if you need a big, spacious, and private place for dinner on special occasions.< /review>< Pics>

< Text>
I love this place. I finally got a serious turntable / receiver / speaker setup back in November and these guys have been my go-to. Their new section is on point but so is their used stuff. And every used record I've gotten from them has been in near mint condition. They are affordable and give you 10% off if you spend $100. They are also incredibly safe and conscious of the pandemic. Highly recommend.< /Text>

<text>Great find!

First of all, the music welcomes. I heard jazz, punk, pop, electronic. I need to know more about the playlist. This alone made the visit super enjoyable.

Second, there is so much vinyl. Huge bins of random used records, 45s and LPs, for cheap- most for 99¬¢. There is also a well-organized section of higher quality items; new stuff, used stuff in great shape, some collectible things. I wish I could have spent more time.

Third, there are lots of CDs, used and new, and even a decent selection of used DVDs.

The place wasn't packed, but there were several customers browsing around.  You get the feeling the product is turning over. The proprietor was super nice, is clearly passionate about music, and promoting a quality experience.

Go.<//text>< pics>

< text>
This is a great store, reminiscent of the many great record stores that used to lie on Ventura BLVD in the '70s and '80s before the internet came wiped them out. Very nice selection of CDs (great condition and very reasonable prices), and LPs.  One can listen to used recordings before buying them.  Highly recommended if you live in the Valley. This store is of a dying breed, take advantage of it while its still around.<//text>

<Resp>{'time': 1618341963102, 'text': 'Thank you Amanda for the feedback on Gondola safety and out sanitizing protocols. We have forwarded this to the Operations Department so they can also see your feedback. We are happy you enjoyed your Zoo visit'}</Resp><username>Amanda Cheung</username><rate>4<//rate>< review>
Came here last weekend on a Sunday for our schedule visit at 2:30pm. My boyfriend and I booked our tickets two weeks in advance for $24 each per adult and $10 for parking. Recommend to book ahead of time for your time slot, which allows you up to 30 minutes to enter, meaning from 2:30-3pm is our entry time. The lines were short and ample parking for visitors. Most animals were out and about but the reptiles and bugs building was closed and play structures are closed off from kids due to covid protocols. There‚Äôs a free gondola to take to see more animals at the top and the lines went by fast. Reason why gave one star less is because of the cleaning and sanitizing they are doing at the zoo. I felt that the way the gondolas were being sanitized could be better. They are sanitizing by just a quick spray of disinfectant into the gondola vs spraying the seats and wiping down spots that may be touched. People are getting hand sanitized before they enter but I also saw a few families slip by without doing so. I personally would feel more safe with them being more strict on their workers to follow and clean when not everyone has had their chance at receiving the vaccine yet. However, this zoo is worth checking out if you haven‚Äôt before. Not a whole lot of animals to see compared to other zoos but the gondola seems like an attraction to many that‚Äôs different from other Bay Area zoos.</review>

<response>{'time': 1619723667562, 'text': 'Thanks for the detailed review !'}< /response><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNTSaoRj9vU1ZaHgwo6XJXozdNUHoHnoXPov-ZM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMOcGz0T1DpcSpa4SRTmxbbJcmFaIxO2zOiTgT1=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhpZ0eHp0oFLHv-fScnnGmOam0_p5jHLIX9CyY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPfwssSQHxZ1ZfvaDS4DWNL9NLaLl8Ph9P-2pJe=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO6lvWIfiq0AFnzKYnqVRR234_tZxoqM1n_MZDP=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOYFG9j1XLsGZYXxqKJBwx7afwuHbhL4kV8DZWG=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><time>1619617771988</time>< Text>
Fun zoo for all! Perfect for kids. The zoo itself is located up in the Oakland Hills, giving it a very unique backdrop. If you have a membership to another zoo, you can get discounted tickets at 50% off and free parking (parking normally $10). Check to see if your zoo is listed on the "Reciprocal list" to qualify for this discount, although the only way to purchase these discounted tickets is in person. The zoo hasn't built this into their online reservation system. For all others, if visiting during COVID, you'll need to reserve tickets online. Many cool animals, a freaking gondola ride üòÉ and probably the best zoo food options I've seen. The food although expensive, was fresh and tasty. They serve beer!! Zoo is the perfect size, not too big, not too small. I think they also have a carousel and train ride, which were closed because of COVID. The gondola ride was a highlight and comes with the price of admission. You could ride it as many times as you want and the views are awesome. Food court and more animals are located at the top of the gondola ride</Text>

< Review>
I haven't been to this zoo in many years and I was shocked to see how awesome and beautiful it has become. The new gondola and upper area of the Zoo was an amazing update. The animals have so much space to roam around and the overlook of the cities makes you feel like you are on top of the world. The online ticket purchase was super easy and the crowd was definitely perfect for a Wednesday afternoon. I'm sure it sells out on the weekend. Definitely wear good comfy walking shoes as the hilly terrain is rough for some. I definitely forgot how hilly this place was. Lol. But it's not a huge place so it doesnt feel overwhelming and like you have to rush to see it all. Its perfect!</Review>

<response>{'time': 1617057994778, 'text': 'Thanks for the detailed review!'}</response><Name>Lou ggle< /Name><date>1617059904954</date>< review>
Great time! Awesome to walk around. Food available. Try to get an early RSVP, 2 weeks in advance for weekends. Weekday's schedule are usually open depending on the day. Don't just drive there, pay for everything online including parking pass. Make sure to at least have the ticket barcodes from email pdf available on phone to enter park. Had a blast! Snack shop has hot food & drinks but hot food don't last all day; they ran out by 3pm. But everything else was great! We got food, walked around with mask on, and of course 6 ft social distancing. Employees will create lines if too many people are wanting to view the same animal to prevent overcrowding 1 area. Staff was excellent!<//review>

<Name>D Nguyen< /Name><text>Our family really enjoyed the Glowrati event! There was just the right amount of people. The flow of the lines and the atmosphere was relaxing. Food & concessions were open for purchase, however we brought our own snacks. The weather was amazing and not that chilly the evening of 11/28. You can enter within an hour of your reservation time on your tickets and you can stay as long as you want until closing at 10 pm. The earlier, the better I think. Parking was easy because of it and we got the first space in front of the entrance, which never happens. Everybody was wearing masks even though we were outside. The gondola ride up the hill was open and you can fit a double back-to-back stroller inside, not sure about the tandem. Super convenient because we didn't have to take the kids out. We have the Contour. It was a great little family outing for the Thanksgiving weekend. There were bubbles and a big floor piano for the kiddos to stomp on along with music, however for those who are strict about the social distancing among kids, probably best to divert to a different location.<//text></record></dataset><record>

< Review>
A nice zoo for kids and the family. Right now you book a time/date in advance and the spots do fill up so you'll want to plan ahead. We went in the afternoon and many animals were active. There were lots of staff on site to answer questions and keep things moving. Most people respected wearing a mask and social distancing. There were some spots that got a bit crowded but you could always find space.<//Review>

< text>
Having a pass is the best way to go (single, family or whatever). Fantastic for kids, our 3 y/o goes frequently and she never seems to tire of it. You can find all the animals and attractions online. The gondola (free) offers fantastic views of the SF Bay, as does the upper landing. Although some attractions are currently closed (thanks 'rona), like chimps, mountain lions (vulnerable to covid) and indoor spots with tight quarters (reptiles, insects), and petting zoo, there are still plenty of things to see.<//text>

<Text>Visited in Aug 2020 a few weeks after reopening. Purchased timed-entry tickets and parking online ahead of our visit, as currently required. Went with a senior, who appreciated the many benches for resting on. Pleasant employees. Employees and visitors followed the mask requirement. This was our first visit using the gondola to the California Trail loop. Beautiful addition to the zoo! Great to see local animals as well as ones from around the world. Some of the "welcome back" messages on whiteboards throughout the park named individual animals; I would love to have that information posted more permanently for the larger/older/easy to identify animals. Some areas of the zoo are currently closed (amusement park, petting zoo), so check the website if you have a particular destination in mind.<//Text>< date>

Beautiful zoo with an excellent assortment of animals that are very obviously well taken care of! The ride up to California Trail offers spectacular views and even more cool animals. This zoo is great for people of any age and isn't too expensive. Staff all seem to love working there and are knowledgeable and helpful. Definitely recommend spending a day here!< /Review>

Although several areas were still closed where social distancing is not possible, we were still able to enjoy nearly all of the zoo. Staff were plentiful, friendly, and knowledgeable. Habitats looked so nice I could live there. And the burger and fries at the cafe were awesome. The hills can be a bit steep for mobility challenged patrons, but there are plenty of benches and lots of shade to rest a bit. The animals looked happy and healthy with many enrichment activities and areas for them.<//text>

Great place to visit...Best for kids..All day fun..The visiting fee was 24 dollars per person..So many species of animals are there.. Their is a show where at the end of the show u can touch animals which was fun.. I touched Python...Food is good.. Their are three adventure rides one is gondola ride which will be free if you buy admission tickets of 24 dollars.. second one is another trip which is of 6 dollars which is little boring good for kids and the third one is on train where u have to buy 2 tickets per person in this trip we will see Australian species..It is full on fun... Restrooms are available..We have to stand in queues for all the adventure trips.. The zoo will closes at 5...</Review>

<rate>4</rate>< Text>
We had a great time. It was great for our older kids but for our preschool age kids not so much. All the play areas and  petting zoo were all closed.  Water fountains all turned off and only the stores open at the entrance. Bring your own beverages or buy it when you first get there because all the usual eating spots are closed. Everything else was closed. Was not worth the entrance fee when everything for the kids is off limits. The time limit also has you feeling rushed. Gives you barely enough time to get around the whole zoo. With little ones it a little harder. The ride up the mountain was amazing. We all enjoyed it and loved all the animals up there. Again, wish the play areas were open and water fountains. But with Covid it all has to be closed. I just don‚Äôt think it was worth the $120 we paid to get in when all the kids stuff were closed off. Especially petting zoo.</Text>

<userid>108453675463629554167< /userid>< name>
Karen V Chin</name>
< Date>
1563242222361< /Date>
<rate>5</rate>< review>
Wonderful place for the whole family to go explore, learn, and have fun together. There is the zoo, the panoramic gondola üö† ride in which you can see the Bay Area (strollers and wheel chair friendly), and Adventure Landing (Kiddy amusement park for toddlers to 8 year olds).

Can easily see and experience the zoo and Adventure Landing in less than 6 hours.

#LetsGuide Tip: Be sure to ride the gondola as part of your experience, the panoramic Bay Area views are spectacular - can see all of the East Bay, Oakland Airport, San Francisco, etc.‚Äî there are bears, mountain lions, bald eagles, etc. to see, a cafeteria with self serve outdoor dining area a ‚Äúmultimillion dollar view,‚Äù and a zip line for kids to enjoy.

The zoo itself is hilly (many rolling hills) so if you are pushing a stroller or wheel chair it can be a workout.

Restrooms have diaper changing tables. Lots of outdoor dining areas that you can either purchase food or bring your own and eat.

Besides zoo ticket costs, parking cost is $10/car.

During the week, the place is filled with school groups and summer camp attendees besides families. There are certain areas where there can be a lot of kids in one place because of this.</review>

<user>112844355168946793338< /user><Name>Harsha N</Name><date>1562637388004</date><rating>3< /rating>< Text>
I added the photographs of almost all the major animals I saw except the lions. You will pretty good number of animals in the zoo. However I felt the animal enclosures ate really very small for them. When we are actually captivating them, we should atleast be sure that they get the minimum place to roam around. I honestly don‚Äôt think they gave enough space. Apart from the images added we saw grizzlies, grey wolves and a jaguar. There are about four grizzlies, one jaguar and two wolves with their four pups. It was great to see them. We were lucky enough to reach the point during their feeding time. We could see the grey wolf carry food for the pups and also saw it hiding the food at many different places. The trains ride is for kids ONLY. Sky ride is worth it coz you have good chances of siting a lion from the top during the ride. Would have been a great place if the animals were given enough room.</Text>

<text>I heard from many friends that this zoo was amazing and now I know first hand. Fantastic zoo for animals that can't be in their natural habitats with room to roam. The animals have space!!! Imagine that!?! And the prices are very reasonable (even has a discount online for membership- worth every cent and includes parking).
During this pandemic unfortunately a lot of exhibits are off limits and closed for obvious reasons but we still enjoyed  ourselves immensely and plan on coming back again soon. The zoo really needs the community's support to help sustain the animals needs.

When fully reopened (hopefully in the near future) there are kid play zones and viewing areas thoughtfully placed all around the park, an awesome gondola, a train and children amusement park area.
I didn't get to try the cafe (my only complaint) the cafe up near the Buffalo and bears was closed and I was starving and munching on my kids snacks üòê.</text><Time>1598931138956</Time><name>Alisha Rivera</name><Resp>{'time': 1599079180717, 'text': "Thank you for leaving a review Alisha! We did a walk-in.

Start your April Fool‚Äôs Day in Oakland Zoo. ü¶íü¶¨üêÜü¶ìü¶©ü¶ùüê´üêäü¶çüêòüê¢

Jun‚Äôs Tips:
1. Take a Bart and a Uber to the zoo.
2. Eat the Dipping Dots in the store (you rarely find it in supermarket; the banana split is good)
3. See the California Grizzly Bear. It‚Äôs the State bear.
4. Oversee SF and Oakland on top.
5. Eat their burger üçî in the canteen (the patty is moist like steamed. I like it. Not too dry or heated. )
6. Check out @christianlambertphoto for more photos of the Zoo.

Michael‚Äôs tip:
1. Go to the S.F. Embarcadero to talk about if you are going to come (you may not want to come)
2. Always love your husband.
3. Enjoy!

< Review>
Admission price is 24 dollars and there is a mandatory parking fee of 10 dollars. The entrance is up far on purpose with no pedestrian access. When inside, there are some rides that require more fees. The food concessions are overpriced - bring food and water from home! The zoo itself is pretty decent and not dilapidated even if many animals look pretty old. However at these prices it's a place for the rich. The upper part with the gondola is actually quite nice but all day I had to think how much I will have to work to pay for the whole family to enter here :(</Review>

< review>
A great experience to travel through this nicely constructed zoo space. It's really nice to see that the animals are given good amount of space and the enclosures are widely separated and spread across the area. There are also some fun facts and important information alongside the route and the enclosures which is fun to read. The ropeway that takes you up to the bear spot offers a great view of the Bay area. So all in all a great place to visit.</review>

['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPQblVvr9i-ZIhxfO8eJaWPwi33UqKJ08yvORpb=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics><Rate>5<//Rate>< Gmap_id>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /Gmap_id>
< Text>
The Oakland Zoo is absolutely one of the best zoos in the Bay Area.  It is clean, well laid out, family friend, well kept and fun.  It is apparent that the animals are well cared for and a lot of thought has been put into their habitats.  It is very easy to spend the entire day walking this spacious zoo.

All of my life we have been coming to the Oakland Zoo and my memories of it are from childhood to adulthood are wonderful and precious.  We have take nieces, nephews and now grand-babies here.

The Oakland Zoo is a Bay Area Gem and it promotes wildlife education and conservation.  If you go to its website you can access their wildlife cameras and watch the Sun Bears, Black Bears, Elephants and Condors live.  It is an excellent place to spend a day relaxing individually or as a family and build your own special memories.  This is a must do if you are any type of animal lover!  Don't miss the train ride, merry-go-round or especially the Gondola/Sky-Hi ride that gives you spectacular views of the SF Bay Area.   We love this Zoo, its animals and the team of people who make this place so magically wonderful.  Enjoy!<//Text>

<name>Andy Chittum</name><text>Have enjoyed the Zoo in the past, and had some trepidation about going anywhere during Covid, but they have several measures in place to limit exposure.  Reservations were easy to get online, and the limited number of people made it easy to stay distanced while seeing the animals.  The gondola was constantly being disinfected, and really enjoyed the new native California area up on the hill.  Good option for doing something outside with the family.<//text></record>

< UserId.>
105780211507192499626</UserId.>
<user_name>V Tancredi<//user_name>< date>
1566693349520<//date>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
Decently large zoo with a great variety of different animals. Very family friendly, multiple Cafe's, play areas.

There's a mini amusement park at the top parking lot complete with a train.

In the last couple of years they made a great expansion to the crest of the Oakland hills. You take a wonderful gondola ride to the upper facility, where you are treated to constant panoramic views of the bay area.

There is a large cafe, play area and new exhibits of native fauna such as bears, wolves, mountain lions, condors, eagles etc.

They also have a buffalo area where they help raise buffalo to repopulate a herd being reinstated by a native American tribe.

If you do nothing else take the gondola ride and have a bite at the cafeteria. Most impressive.
Be prepared to take a walk for parking though. They have multiple large lots but the place is very very popular and gets crowded by families every weekend.< /Text>

< Review>
This zoo is huge. Easy to find parking space, family oriented. They got bathrooms, animal play ground for kids, gift shop, cafe. Different animals birds, monkeys, lions, tigers, giraffes, zebras, elephants and so much more. The zoo is very nice and clean and employees are nice, friendly and helpful. I would totally recommend worth every dollar.</Review>
< rating>
5< /rating>

<Review>The zoo is big and the animals have a lot of space to roam around. The giraffe area could be expanded though. There are already six of them plus other animals and the ducks. Their area seems small for so many animals. This zoo does not have as many animals as one would expect. Still a nice zoo. This year the area was expanded and the Gondolas were added. You could ride them up to a new cafeteria section for free. The view of the whole Bay Area is spectacular especially on a clear day. Food here is quite expensive. A cup of coffee costs almost $5.</Review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNvmh0sA55BINg1c1YqfEztXz2DOiN87lGOiqEo=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': <review>ProTip: Don't go when it's raining and/or cold. We went on a Saturday around 10:30 and it was lightly raining. The sign at the entrance said to decide if you want to go because the zoo might close. Luckily it didn't, but the animals weren't fans of the rain. The least kept up exhibit was the insect building; it also smelled pretty bad inside. Overall it was a good visit, especially the gondola ride to the California Trail. Also, to get a better view of the Bay than the bison overlook, go to the outdoor area of the nearby "visitor's center," which is actually a restaurant.</review><Pictures>[{'url': < Review>
Great zoo! I loved seeing the animals, but even better is you can tell this zoo is animal friendly and cares about them and not just bringing in money. They are also very environmentally friendly which is a plus! They have canned water instead of plastic water bottles! There are also very good views of the Bay Area here! The animal signs are very informative and interesting!< /Review>

< review>
Really nice exhibits to view the animals and get some nice photographs. Great selection of animals including elephants. The tram to the new facility/restaurant is free and the food was suprisingly good. The staff was friendly and helpful. A few places could use some maintenance but the overall experience was outstanding. Looking forward to going back. Get there earlier than later as parking can fill up quickly.< /review>

<date>1542176091071< /date>< Rating>

<review>In all fairness the day we went was windy so the gondola was not running, and there were horrendous fires burning just north. When the gondola is not working, you can only access a smaller part of the zoo. The upper part of the zoo was totally off-limits since there was no gondola ride to take you up there.  That's a whole third of the zoo . So we missed out on a lot. The air was thick and Smokey. But even beyond that, I was a disappointed in the zoo. It needs a lot of TLC. You can definitely tell it is an older Zoo. The animals look well cared for and there are a lot of well-informed docents to answer questions or provide information. Some of the things that weren't that great, were the lack of a signage to get you around the zoo, the many empty cages and enclosures, the poor quality of the ground you walk on, lots of big gaps and cracks and bumps that are kind of dangerous, lack of good signage on the foliage around the zoo which truly does make it interesting. And lack of any type of commentary on the little train ride that is given. There was no, "Welcome to the train ride", no standard, " keep your arms and legs in the train ride", not even descriptions of the animals that we slow down to see from the train. It definitely needs an overhaul. Better training on behalf of the people that provide the train ride too.</review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMdGfUVdDbDwbnb5enyATDSd3Xsdr9ObdqDm8m9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPt1HDVx8E3BPgmjJI_-xf8umtAGNLC0Br_EKkY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM8usqB7cw-WcFTOJYmZkJCiZrHxdOvitt1Z50_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPZO6l06l-A_6DVn7maXBCfvASB2jI88pcA0IvI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPALGrACLU2y41wjxkiMVbpDL68UP_gIa7Qvimd=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMl5OgZyc-XTDhgzM13-EjBc-momfdGg8sAH03o=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMmXWokRuUq5PIjod9dfu7ImjJMTaHxSL3kCTLT=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO5pAIEeb3JAfI3DeicRP1YbJPbUOwIVti3fiis=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNd_MXGJIgXkS8FLqJcWLro1apl1YWNt6U6jN1U=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP_ZSgja2IZYaTGrZdzzjsLe07H1yAFVh7xyWWH=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOVGwb25sSoC3qg3d4tmjgNhw6nWqsqw2K9Jept=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNpT01tZkaz7_Z9gbjQbrZk3EBiUDdm65xbwiVL=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>< Resp>

<Gmap_id>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /Gmap_id><Review>What a pleasant surprise! Oakland does not have the best reputation, and I figured that I might be disappointed. I was wrong. So wrong. The zoo is well-maintained, the animals were well cared for, and it was fin for both the adults and children. The California enclosures are currently being built, but you can take the gondola up to the top of the zoo property for a spectacular view. From the cafe you can see a HUGE section of the bay, including the ship yards, bridges, and the city below. It is a bit breezy up there to say the least, so make sure to bring a sweater on cooler days. The zoo is great for photographers, with both animals and beautiful gardens to capture. We did not have enough time to see everything, even though we were there for 3.5 hours. We pass through the area often and will definitely be back. San Francisco Zoo has some neat exhibits, but many of the buildings and habitats are closed and rotting away. SF Zoo is mostly flat, whereas the Oakland Zoo is carved into the side of a small mountain. I have mobility issues, and the hills wore me out, so plan some extra time to stop and rest along the way if you have difficulty walking or tire easily. This zoo reminded me a lot of the San Diego Zoo, albeit on a bit smaller scale.< /Review>< Date>
1522000604203< /Date>

< Time>
1519082090043<//Time>
< review>
I've traveled to many zoos and this one remains one of my favorites. It has a nice variety of animals and interactive experiences for kids and adults alike. My family has had a family membership for the Oakland Zoo for the past five years, and I encourage everyone who wants to visit to buy a membership. Being a member gives you free parking, early notification of new events, and has reciprocal benefits at most zoos across the country. I also recommend arriving early if you want to see the lions and tigers active opposed to just sleeping in their habits.</review>
</record></dataset><record>

<rate>5< /rate>< review>
Great Zoo! The upper area, that can be reached with the gondola, is a must as this is what really completes the experience. The bottom part is a bit old and could be rejuvenated but the overall ambiance is not destroyed by these details that could be improved. Most employees are great to deal with, especially the ones that handle animals and are clearly passionate about it. I write "most" because I ran into 1 exceptionally silly person who didn't give me enough tickets, which I had paid for, for the train and then made me pay again... but oh well, wasting $3 wasn't really worth running my day by arguing with an idiot...<//review>

< Response>
{'time': 1597166951250, 'text': 'Thanks Brian for the great and thoughtful review! This is definitely a learning opportunity for us and feedback like this is extremely helpful in creating new protocols to keep our guests safe.'}</Response>
<rating>5</rating>< Review>
We went Sunday August 2nd a few days after they opened again. Overall it was a great experience! The animals seemed more active than I remember, so maybe they were happy to see us again. Even the jaguar wasn't pacing.

The staff did a pretty good job considering the constraints they had to work under. They had people at various places directing everyone and I still saw many of them really enjoy talking with the guests while keeping safe.

There were a few downsides. While almost everyone wore a mask as directed, it was difficult at certain key places to keep 6 feet apart. Especially at the entrance there were a lot of people at the gift shop while we were trying to walk in. If they could temporarily move the gift shop somewhere else, that would be ideal I think.

Second, it was very difficult to keep kids from touching the glass. There are signs and people walking around reminding people not to touch the glass but it is difficult. Our kids did a fairly good job at it but still was very difficult to completely avoid.

Third, they did a great job cleaning each gondola as people got out, but the bottom had 3 separate lines and it was difficult for them to go in order and keep cleaning. I feel like they had the toughest job. They should do a single line at the bottom just like they do at the top.

Hopefully they are able to keep everything open, we would like to be able to keep going safely!<//Review>

< rating>
5< /rating>
< Review>
Great zoo, spread out so it doesn't feel crowded. The new California trail is a must see with lots of activities for kids. The bear exhibit was huge and we got to see the beard up close! My 5 year old spent a lot of time playing on the playground in the trail, and the cafeteria is a great place to lunch before heading back down the hill.

I highly recommend as a day trip, is even 2 days to split up the California trail and the rest of the zoo, but get there early so you don't have to worry about parking or stand in a huge line to ride the free gondola.<//Review>

< Review>
Great way to spend an afternoon. Half a day should be enough time to get around and see the main things.
Some of the highlights for us were the Gibbons on their island. Be sure not to miss them.
A couple of other things worth seeing are the flying foxes on the way out are also definitely worth a visit ( mainly since you don‚Äôt see those very often) and also the reptile house (very nicely done with a few different terrariums and very active little guys to see).<//Review>

Great zoo. Nice size for a one day visit. Wheelchair and stroller accessible. Very few people on a weekday.  My son loves the gondola and the staff is very friendly about letting you ride over and over again, especially when they are not busy. Some great views of the lions from the sky ride. My son also loves the rides outside the park .</review>

< review>
I was troubled by the lack of space the Oakland Zoo provides for the Bald Eagle. The Eagle expressed distress when I was last there. The Eagle would repeatedly fly to the top of the nettting as if trying to escape. Any sentient being desperately trying to escape to freedom is one of the saddest and traumatic things to witness.
The zoo does not provide nearly enough space for a bird that is known for flying at high altitudes.
I wish they would release the Eagle(s) to a more fitting and spacious animal reserve if there is no possibility of rehabilitation back into the wild.<//review>
<Pics>None< /Pics><userid>112937034942891384464</userid><user_name>Moon< /user_name>< Rate>

< Text>
I hadn't been to a zoo since I was a little kid and this one was quite fun and a chill experience. There was a wide variety of creatures to look at and I got the feeling they took good care of them. If you're looking for a relaxed way to spend an afternoon, this is the way to do it. They are opening a new section of the zoo in July that I didn't get to see but it looks very promising, with larger exhibits that try to place the animals in something more like their natural habitats. You even get to ride a lift with an amazing view up to the new area where there is a caf√© with the same view. We were able to go up to the caf√©, but not into the new area of the zoo.</Text>

<review>It is positively delightful, beautiful and very clean. It cost $24 for admission plus tax. Tickets can be purchased there and online. With this, it's free to ride the gondola up to the California Trail. Skyrides cost an extra $3. Note, it is really cold up there now(December) so dress appropriately. Also, make sure you wear comfortable shoes coz you will walk alot. Parking cost $10 so you can park across the zoo and walk to the gate. Finally, it is a fun place for adults and children. Enjoy!< /review><Time>1576677071810<//Time></record></dataset><record>

< Review>
Very nice newly constructed upper area.  Great view of the bay.  Fun play structure for the kids.  Better than expected food at the new cafe.  Garlic fries is a must try. Feeding for the bear was also fun to watch.  Not as nice as the San Diego zoo but the price is also much digestible.</Review>

<user>100649908151552047645</user>< review>
Great place to go. The new gondola has a great view and the food is excellent. However, the food is expensive. The train ride is ok but you should really go see the new exhibit. You can also take a few photos from the top. Its expensive to get in but, if you like animals, you will not be disappointed.</review>

<rate>4<//rate>< text>
I enjoyed the zoo very much. It seems well kept and well managed. It is a scenic walk even if there were no animals.  The big Surprise for me was the gondola ride to the east side of the park offering stunning views of the Bay. The structures on that side of the park were  beautiful including the cafe and the wooden decks/platforms made for walking, standing and viewing. I liked the environment throughout the zoo where the animals are kept (the enclosures) from The birds to the tigers.
What I didn't expect, was to have to pay $10 for parking. I also thought the admission fee might be less than what it was. I don't know what the average price of admission for zoos are Nationwide, but it seems a little high to me. Maybe it's just because I haven't been to a zoo in a while or maybe it's because it's located in California.< /text>

<Rating>5< /Rating><Text>A Place where my grandparents visited while they were dating, and subsequent alternative to Fairyland, the Oakland zoo has held up well after, nearly a century of operation, and adapted with the times, and practices of some much bigger zoos in the United States.
One of our favorites was the Chimp there, (At least I think it was a chimp, hey what do you want, I was like, 5) who would mimic us kids and sometimes tag us with a piece of candy or a nutshell.
This is Oakland History. AND somehow still unknown to many younger East Bay residents. Change that! Go and visit!<//Text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Response>

< text>
The zoo is decent now, but will almost double in size with wolves, bears and more lions in summer 2018. While some areas are a bit of a let down, it has already a wide variety of animals and habitats including the very entertaining train ride through the Australian Outback (paid separately as is with the sky ride).

Definitely use the free Gondola to go uphill even if you come before summer 2018, the view is very worthwhile and the right company will make it a very nice experience.<//text>

I have come here 3 time since last year. I have come to enjoy very much Oakland's zoo  The first time the draught showed a terrible impact on the zoo's vegetation and animal and the ambiance was dusty but on February and may the park looked amazing and the animals also enjoyed the new condition as well. I love taking the sky ride to go to the upper part and the views. There is quite a good variety of animals throughout the zoo and the bears,  jaguar, tigers, and elephants are quite impressive. I definitively recommend a family membership if you live in the area and come multiple times throughout the year.<//review>

We started off with the Sky Ride (an extra $3 per person) and got to see over the giraffes, lions and elephants. From there we went to see the baboons, siamang and monkeys and birds. They have a really nice collection of insects, but there were only a few reptiles in the other area. < review>
It's a really good place to take kids with various animals to watch along with rides.. Rides include a sky ride, gandola, train ride and also few more kids rides. Lot of educational information written all along the path. Gandola ride is beautiful and that ride is included in the zoo entrance fee. They have restrooms everywhere.
They have ample parking along with shuttles to help people get to the entrance. And also very clean and well maintained.</review>

<text>Took my daughter and her cousin here, it‚Äôs been almost two years since we visited. They enjoyed it, saw the huge tigers and giraffe, the pet zoo was fun for them. The giant tortoises too.<//text>< Pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO5kEkMUSx7QJqztRbC0Th8OplHfVWoirTgm8St=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM8Lvqr388ML-djTlXmyMfi3crPV-1Y2zuoMOp_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures>

0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /Gmap_id>

<rating>5< /rating>< text>
While at the outset , I was unsure of what fan fare to expect for a hefty $24 entry fee , I was pleasantly surprised at what the zoo had to offer. Starting with the maps which my toddler could interpret owing to the animal silhouettes that line up, through the Australian safari on a clickety clack steam train, up the sky ride over the lion, camel and the elephants, going further up to the enclosed gondola giving not only a magnificent view of the cities,but also taking one to the California Trail, the zoo just rocks.

From a toddler's perspective it was sheer delight given the fact that I eased his walks with a stroller to go everywhere. The trails are covered with greenery making the walks a non issue even on a hot day. Conveniently placed stores , restrooms and water stops make enjoying the animals your only option! I was impressed with the magnificence of the African section with the Giraffes, Elephants and Elands.

I would highly recommend this place for a full day trip with your family. The well maintained trails, the carefully manicured enclosures with ample space and human created mimicry of natural features like stone walls, deserts, water falls etc along with geographically apt flora make the fauna come to life.<//text>
<time>1531924334111</time>< Name>
Pradeep Varadan< /Name>

< review>
Went to the Zoo on Saturday. This is a very beautiful Zoo we love the terrain and how well kept it is. I was really disappointed at how crowded it was. I felt really uncomfortable at how many people the Zoo let in at once. It was very hard to social distance because it was that crowded. I did appreciate the staff cleaning the high touch surfaces and keeping the Zoo clean.<//review>

< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<user_name>Lauren Riot</user_name><userid>118190516377173687461</userid>< review>
The covid protocols are pretty simple to navigate and reassuring. Buy tickets or reserve with your membership online and have them printed or on your phone when you arrive. The Baboon bridge gets too crowded to be safe, if that's a special one for your kid(s) be aware it may not be on the itinerary. The mask rules for kids are above and beyond state recommendations (a good thing, most kids can keep a mask on), however the staff did not harass me when my developmentally disabled child who is older than 3 refused to keep his mask on halfway through our visit. We were able to distance further from people at that point because it is not crowded at all. Gondolas are sprayed with disinfectant after each use and hand sanitizer is provided before boarding. All in all a very stress free outing after months of staying home.< /review>

<Name>Miguel Cuellar<//Name><time>1536326282343< /time>< rate>
5</rate>
< Review>
Oakland zoo is large and you can easily spend the WHOLE day here. Wear some comfortable shoes, some of the paths will be going uphill/downhill. Bring a stroller for younger children as they may get tired from walking, but it you forget it, they do have stroller rentals available. Bathrooms are located throughout the park as well as drinking stations and food kiosks. There are several feeding times throughout the day and trainer talks. They have an app you can download that helps with the schedules and also map of the zoo. They have a new California trail that recently opened. You'll have to take a skyline ride to get to it. There are also several kids play area throughout so you can let them play run around a bit and you can sit have a break lol<//Review>

<Rating>3</Rating><Review>COVID UPDATE: A sizable portion of the zoo is closed as of the writing of this review. All of the drinking fountains are closed so expect to bring your own water or prepare to purchase the aluminum water bottles.

Only one refill station is available immediately after the gondola.

Masks on all the time rule was okay with me and my party but may be difficult for those with breathing problems especially on hot days like when I went (93¬∞F).

If you want to support the zoo, think about donating via their website. Otherwise, save your money for the full reopening.< /Review>< Pics>

<rating>4< /rating><review>Went to the zoo this october and it was really nice. The zoo limits the number of people who can come to the zoo through their reservation system online and the entrance fee is not expensive at all. There is few exibits for food near the entrance (which closes by 3pm) and a stand that sells snacks inside so either pack a lunch for your family or eat before going to the zoo. Any part of the zoo that is enclosed is closed. The animals seem to love it since it's very quiet. We enjoyed it and spent about 4 hours there. Plenty of areas with sanitizer stations.< /review><pictures>None< /pictures><resp>{'time': 1603817380298, 'text': 'Thanks for the review!'}< /resp>< gmapID>

<userid>100373269539123503599< /userid><gmapID>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /gmapID>< text>
So fun! We have annual family passes and they paid for themselves in just 3 visits. Since we don't have to pay every time we go in we pop by for lunch (the food is really lame but the view is unbeatable), take friends and family, ride the gondola at sunset.

I love the giraffes, elephants, hilarious monkeys, bats, camels. The baboons are AWESOME , always running around, playing tag, wrestling. And there's all ages from a tiny baby baboon that hangs out on it's mom's back to a big cool old dude who just chills while the others wait on him all day.

The kids area at the Oakland zoo is perfect, too --both my 3 yo niece and 9yo nephew could both really enjoy almost all the rides (he was too tall for just one of them). And they have a Little Free Library on one of their nature paths!<//text>

< review>
My kids and I loved the zoo and especially the gondola! Bring your money though! Entry is pricey and so is food and drink but you gotta figure it's going to the animals so...
We stayed all day and didn't even realize we were there till closing time. That's how much fun we had! There's a lot to see so make sure you're there early or you wont be able to see it all. There are even some rides to enjoy when you're ready to take a break from walking!<//review>

<review>This zoo went through a recent expansion adding what is known as the California Trail.  Basically more than doubling the previous Zoo size.  Bald Eagles, Condors, Cougers, Black Bears, Grizzly Bears and more.  Keep in mind this in addition to what was previously there, like Tigers, Lions, Elephants, oh my and more.  With the expantion comes a higher price too, but you get to see so much more as well.  An added bonus is the views of San Francisco are pretty awesome from this new portion of the Zoo.</review>< pictures>

The staff at Adventure Park are outwardly disgruntled and yell back and forth about how much they hate operating the rides, distracting kids and families who are having fun. < user>
116429050914568115542</user>
< Review>
Love the Oakland Zoo! The animals have large enclosures and the zoo keepers are always out and about willing to discuss animal diets and habits with children. The new gondola takes you to a whole new conservation walk area and restaurant. Start with the flamingos and turn right to walk counter clockwise around the zoo path. Tigers, giraffes, camels, lions, birds, elephants, zebras, meercats, hyenas, wart hogs, baboons, crocodiles, bugs, petting zoo, pigs, goats, sheep, bats, otters, turtles, lemurs, giant tortoises, toucans, monkeys, sun bears (often hiding in that beautiful enclosure), deer and more I'm sure I missed. Fun to enjoy again and again. Buy a family membership for free parking and more discounts.</Review>

Marina Alvidrez</name>

<rating>5< /rating>< text>
First time back during Covid.  We had a great morning.  All staff was very friendly.  Felt very comfortable.  Everyone had masks on and gave great social distance. Gondola cars are sanitized as one group gets out and before the next group gets in.  We see something different everytime we go.  Today we saw the jaguar eating breakfast, 2 camels laying on their sides right next to the veiwing area and the lions talking to each other.  Saw lots of other animals as well and had a great walk.  Thank you Oakland Zoo.<//text>

< Pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhr92lxUUD6MWm7zlLkg5tnaB8wf1Hgj52ve-b=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMNaiB3Cp3vfJtCY6gLFZvTB8QgwDukLV5bw8Of=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures>
<text>The Oakland Zoo spans some 100 acres and is home to over 750 native and exotic animals. I was not prepared for the hills, inclines and stairs to get in between exhibits. It is nice that there are live people guides to help direct you places and discuss the animals. Visitors can take a train ride and discover the Wild Australia section for emu and wallaroos. The African Savanna area is where the popular giraffes, zebras, and elephants are located.  There are two aerial rides.  The Sky Ride which you have to pay an extra $3 to ride and the gondolas that take visitors to the California Trail and visitor center. There is a panoramic San Francisco Bay overlook worth the wait in line and trip.  There is a lot to see and do at the Oakland Zoo, we did not get to everything this visit but I look forward to the next.</text>< GmapID>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa</GmapID>

<Time>1567286376250< /Time><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
A great zoo with a lot of different animals, spread out over a vast area. Memories as a kid involved the San Francisco Zoo, but I have to say that it is not match compared to the Oakland Zoo. We took the sky gondola to the aminal habitat area, and it was nice to be able to see wolves and other animals in such a large area, but still be observable by patrons. Some great veiws of the Bay as well. My son really enjoyed the different rides available.< /review>

< Rating>
3</Rating>
< review>
The Oakland Zoo is an average Zoo.The species are neither very rare or exotic. Three lions, three tigers, four elephants, 6-7 Giraffes may not make it a world class. Amphibians, reptiles, Birds section was a total disappointment. Though crowded the entry fees and parking fee make it a costly affair. The visitors galleries need quantum improvement for visitors and little children  to have a good look at animals without disturbing  them. The Gandola and train ride can be enjoyed only if exotic varieties and large wild  animals are in plenty.</review>

<user_id>100318707557205030113< /user_id><name>Vishal Mehta< /name>< Date>
1577225549633</Date>
<Rate>4< /Rate><Review>Best zoo in Bay Area!

The design of the exhibits makes it easier to spot animals more naturally. Although there are fences and glass and nets where required, but the experience is friendlier than other zoos I have visited. The size is perfect for completing the tour in a few hours satisfactorily, covering all exhibits.

First thing I would recommend is the Gondola ride, which takes you to the top level of the zoo. Complete that level exhibits and return to the lower level to enjoy the rest.

Food and drinks are allowed, which makes it easier for families to plan. There are plenty of benches and sheltered spots where you can relax and eat before moving on to the viewing.

Unfortunately, the petting zoo and a couple of exhibits were closed due to rainy weather.<//Review>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

<rating>5</rating>< Text>
The Oakland Zoo has done a phenomenal job of handling the COVID crisis! They have employees carrying hand sanitizer dispensers to provide to people in line. They are wiping down public surfaces with a spray disinfectant, and all areas are marked with clearly-visible six-foot designations. Absolutely mind-blowing how perfect their response is and how fully on board each employee is.< /Text>

<review>So much to see and do. You can have a different experience each time you go. Take the gondola to the upper zoo where you'll find a new set of animals to see, an outdoor and indoor play area for kids (including a very popular zipline), and a place to eat. Back down on lower zoo, there's a petting zoo, play area, places to picnic, and a place with rides for kids (train, carousel etc). We go all the time and never get bored.</review><username>Kate Ciungan< /username>< gmapID>

<user>115575979716615255553<//user><user_name>Shiras Corella<//user_name><time>1480830514488< /time>< rating>

< Review>
I've generally hated zoos.  Many zoos have that heartbreaking quality of visiting a prison.  The Oakland Zoo is a bit refreshing in that the animal habitats are generally large and well-appointed, the animals are mostly rescues, and the staff that I've interacted with are passionate and knowledgeable.  It's a nice, sprawling zoo.  Check out the Siamangs and the Flying Foxes (the world's largest fruit bats!).< /Review>
< pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPszHVMXCJ6jbJarPVZDwwFr7ZTsEua7JDb7h0z=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO2DYMXrg5rW-ot7KreCOlBo4GlpjR7rYuckzX9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM_0HtePnDoFq-ra8PmcJ5bstkxohJwFayucnme=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>

<text>We LOVE the Oakland Zoo! This is an excellent place to take your kids, there is so much to see and do. The ticket prices are so reasonable for how much you are getting to see. < text>
This is during Covid...but not entirely related to it.
Pros
-Easy in an out with buying tickets online!
-Nice to see large areas for the Animals!
-Clean bathrooms an areas
- Not gonna complain about exhibits being closed or animals not there etc. Life goes on lol.
-Taking the gondola is cool but read my con lol.

Cons however ....
-I get some food places need to be closed. But there wasn‚Äôt a single vender in the park. Maybe I missed the one right as you walk in. But through the entire park. Not a single food or drink station. I would have left sooner simply to get food, but just trying to walk to every attraction takes forever.

-Complete nightmare walking with a stroller or a child you have to carry. Pathways are uphill or down hill and most areas are a one way in one way out. This is not cause of Covid. It‚Äôs just how the path is. So you have to walk one way to see something to then walk back to get to something else. Poor planning on the layout for sure. Not a single flat area...

-The gondola ride was fun for the kids. A stroller takes up space. Everything was closed or empty but the bears an bison. The bison don‚Äôt do anything an the bear exhibit is the only exhibit worth it. There is also no shade. So unless you wana see a few bears. You can totally skip this. The restaurant is also closed. So no food.

-Not sure of the whole point of a parking pass as it wasn‚Äôt left in my car nor attached to my plate. So I hope that $10  goes to the zoo lol.

Over all it‚Äôs a one an done kinda thing. I enjoyed the Zoo an I am glad they were able to open back up. I didn‚Äôt mind the lack of exhibits etc. I minded the poor planning of the layout of Exhibits an the lack of food and drink.<//text>

< text>
The Oakland Zoo has really come a long way!  Don't expect the caged monkeys in the parking lot! The Oakland Zoo has really taken steps to create a more "natural" environment.  The enclosed gandala up to the "California Area" is a nice alternative to the ski lift that's older than my parents. You don't have to pay zoo admission to get into the kiddie land, but be prepared to pay for ride tickets. In the end a zoo is a zoo. They really aren't that great for anyone and most of the animals are given literal trash to play with. Gatorade bottles do not appear in the wild to entertain anyone! My 2 year old enjoyed herself though, so whatever.< /text>

<rating>4< /rating>< text>
A great place for dates and family outings! The animal husbandry is top quality, and the keepers are excellent at answering questions. The gondola ride up to the California Trail also shouldn't be missed. There's a cafe, plenty of native Californian creatures, and a playground for kids to exhaust themselves (if the walk hasn't done that already). I highly recommend the membership for any local parents, as you certainly get the full value quickly.< /text>

<user_name>Matt Orbach<//user_name><Date>1553319982145< /Date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< text>
Despite going on a weekend that was WAY too crowded (it took 30 minutes just to get off the freeway because the zoo parking lot was so backed up...pretty sure everyone was trying to use their Groupon coupons before they expired), it was a great spot. Beautiful location, good variety of animals, clean facilities. Our daughters loved it, especially seeing Simba and Mufasa (see pics). The only part we didn't do was the California area, but that's because it was in an area only accessible by gondola, and we didn't feel like waiting in the long line and leaving our double stroller with all of our stuff behind (because it wouldn't have fit on the gondola). We'll go back and see that when the girls are older. Overall, definitely worth checking out, though.</text>

My family loves to go to the Oakland Zoo! We haven't been there for a little while, so it was nice to see they have automated the parking lot entrance, and made some improvements to some of the enclosures. Always a great time, lots of friendly families, a real community feeling when you walk the pathways. We'll be back!!!<//review>

This is a great place to bring your kids. They have so many animals and if you come in the morning they are usually active. The gondola ride to the top is also very good as you get the view of the bay. And the ride is free! You'll get to see the bald eagle, wolves, jaguar, bears and mountain lions. This is a fun place for the entire family!</review>

< review>
Really enjoyed our visit to the Oakland Zoo. Tickets are priced pretty reasonably and you can find even better pricing on Groupon. Loads of animals to see. Parking at the lower entrance might be easier if you can find a spot. Spots near the main entrance are taken quickly. Also,  be warned that the road you take up to the main entrance sometimes becomes a one way street so you might have to take a different route down.< /review>

This was fantastic! Free parking was an unexpected surprise. We had a blast of a FUN workout, as we strolled through the lighted Zoo. There was something for everyone's interests.
The light show was fun to watch as the lights changed and seemed to dance with the Christmas music. The Christmas song choices were just as diverse as the attractions throughout the Zoo.
I do recommend this holiday Zoo Lights show for your Christmas, to do list! And, also...
Just remember to remove your plastic lids on your soft drinks/coffee cups before entering. Their not allowed.
Enjoy, Merry Christmas World!
Thanks Oakland Zoo!!< /text>

< review>
Parking is absolutely outrageous on the weekends. Literally took 45 minutes to park. We are members and there is no members line to enter the zoo so you wait in line with everyone buying tickets. They had to close the gondola because so many people were at the top. During the week it is a great zoo with a lot to see and do. I just recommend not going on the weekends. They also do not serve alcohol which the SF zoo does.<//review>

<gmap_id>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /gmap_id>< text>
Perfect size zoo for my two year old. We had a really great time watching the bears. We got there on a Saturday at 11AM. There was a long line to wait for the parking lot entry. The lot was full, and we were instructed to park alongside the curb driving up to the lot. We got on the Gondola first which I highly suggest for two reasons. 1) the line is short, and 2) the other park is small. There's also  The California Wilds Playground on that side which has a sandpit, a small Creek for littles to stick their toes in, a Zipline, a small tunnel and a slide. We then came back to the main park and finished our visit there.</text>

<user_name>Devashish Sarkar</user_name>< Time>

< Response>
None</Response>
<userid>101531998794144797609</userid><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Review>Location on a hill in Oakland off I580.
It should be arguably the best zoo in Bay Area and nearby.
Very reasonably priced, it offers a free Gondola ride up the mountain ( not to be missed) too!!
With our family of four and with 2 kids, we were able to experience 80% of the zoo in 4 hours. We did not do the other sky ride ( paid service). A paid train trip also adds to excitement but it is a very  short ride.
There are about four rides ( carousel, plane, etc) which are OK priced at train station.
It has a reasonable collection of animals and most impressive to us were the primates. The park has lot of birds out of cage and in the wild.  For bird photography, I found ample opportunities. Park has decent food options and several picnic areas.
Overall a good half day trip. Since there are activities too other than exhibits, you could plan multiple trips in the year.</Review></record></dataset><record>
< Pics>
None< /Pics>

< Review>
Such an amazing experience. The animals are well cared for, which is nice to see. The animals are varied and interesting, with good sized, appropriate habitats. Otters, alligator, bats, African animals, and even jaguars and bears. They have this gondola to take visitors to the "California" expanse. Staff is helpful and friendly. Restrooms are well spaced, common and easily accessible. Ramps for wheelchair or stroller access along the exhibits. You will enjoy!<//Review>

< Review>
New California trail up at the top of the gondola is definitely worth checking out. I think the only animals I couldn't spot were the wolves, Grizzlies and mountain lion. They're very well staffed and have knowledgeable zookeepers ready to answer questions. There is a new habitarium up there too, next to the visitor center, also worth a gander, especially if you have kids.<//Review>

Way better than the San Francisco zoo, and half the price. You can spend hours here, especially with little ones. < Review>
This hidden preserve treats the animals with respectful care and wide open spaces. It's a bigger place than you think and the variety of animals is diverse. The food is above average and the gondolas are brand new for easy transport. There are free passes for San Francisco residents and library card holders on some days which can make traffic hectic.  Highly recommended if you avoid those days!< /Review>

<rate>5<//rate>< Text>
Nice place to spend time with your family and friends. Be ready to walk because this place is huge. The exhibit is huge and very safe, be careful with the chimps they're very smart they sometimes throw feces at people who dare to get too close and sometimes hit bystanders. You're warned. They have bears, monkeys, chimps, hyenas, crocodiles, lemurs, elephants, camels, turtles, flamingos, reptiles, insects, jirafs,etc. They have children activities, a little museum elevator, handicap ramps, restrooms, restaurants, aereal gondolas a little train ride, mechanic rides, penny press machines and a gift shop.< /Text>

Very nice place for kids and family...  Lot of animals like giraffe,  elephant,  black bear, grizzly,  fox etc.  The best part is that park has gondola ride inside which takes to the mountain top ... <user_id>101887369019281530005</user_id><user_name>Becky Staaden< /user_name>< Time>
1565542899207< /Time>
<Rating>5</Rating><Review>The zoo has undergone many improvements over the years.  Recently it has added a section on California animals.  The plus side is that it is well laid out, the animals are in natural habitats (which means that they can be really hard to see, they blend in to the grasses, hills, and trees) ...so be prepared to stand around and look for awhile.  This area is only accessible by an overhead cable car.  The plus of this is that it has great views and is fun.  The disadvantage is that the lines can get rather long, especially on Fridays in the summer.
The animal exhibits are well done and many are natural, elephants have hills, lions really really blend into the hillside.
The children's area has lots of play structures to tire the kids out, as well as child oriented animal exhibits (the otters are really popular.)
A good way to spend a day with the family.< /Review><pics>None</pics>< response>
{'time': 1565631560544, 'text': 'Thanks for the detailed review'}</response>

<Date>1546278568068<//Date>< rate>

<Text>Good place for very young kids, ages 3-6. I liked the sea otters the most as well as the gondola ride. I still haven't checked out the new upper portion of the zoo or the reptile house, and will save those for a later date. I did thoroughly appreciate the layout of the zoo and how much space the animals were given. They out a lot of thought into keeping the animals happy. My review is mainly for the membership. This membership is only worth it if you have a family with very young children and you live close to the zoo. I thought it was a well-thought out scam that the amount paid for parking on the day you buy your membership isn't applied towards your membership (since you get free parking with membership) instead you can either apply that amount towards the few dinky rides outside of the zoo or just eat the cost. It is partially my fault for buying a membership my first time at the zoo, without reading further into the consequences of buying a membership.

I am an auntie to about a million children, I have no children of my own, and thought to use the membership to bring my various comadres and their kids to the zoo so we could all spend the day together. I was annoyed that I had to buy the more expensive family plus membership (rather than the regular family), since you have to name both adults, and I needed a membership that would allow myself, 1 adult guest, and several child guests. If I weren't already there with a gaggle of kids, and if I hadn't already paid for parking, I would have just left and not bought the membership.

If you're going to buy a new membership, I would suggest buying the membership online first to avoid the additional cost of paying for parking or just take the bus there.< /Text><Pics>None</Pics>< Response>

<Rate>3< /Rate><review>The good:  I really appreciated the wide variety of animals and exhibits that were on display when I visited, and the zoo's commitment to conservation work and animal welfare seems genuine.  I especially appreciate how they are working with the Siksika/Blackfoot nation to reintroduce wild bison, their rehabilitation of injured and orphaned animals, as well as providing a home for animals who were illegally bought as a pets.

The bad:  I came here with a friend who needed to use a wheelchair, and I was astonished at not only how inaccessible huge areas of the park are to people with disabilities but also how poorly information about accessibility was communicated.  There are wheelchairs available for rent, but they cost $15 (not including a $20 refundable deposit).  Similar museums either charge nothing aside from a deposit or just ask for a photo ID as a security measure.  Even though the wheelchair costs $15 to rent, there is only one size available and it is hard to maneuver.  The only reason it was usable to my friend is because I was available to push it.  Because the wheelchair has non-removable sides, it was very difficult to self-propel even on flat surfaces.  It was completely impossible to self-propel uphill, which is a large portion of the park.  Additionally, many areas of the park are completely inaccessible to non-ambulatory wheelchair users.  My friend was able to walk a short distance with a cane to visit these areas, but not everyone who uses a wheelchair is able to do this.  Given the large number of signs available to orient visitors, it is shocking to me there is no information about which paths might be most accessible, where elevators to avoid stairs could be found, or cautionary information about paths that might have slopes that would be difficult for people with mobility-related disabilities.  The information provided about storing and maneuvering the park with a stroller was far more comprehensive than the instructions provided to individuals in wheelchairs.  I understand that the zoo was started before the ADA, but many of these fixes are relatively simple (e.g., adding informative signage, adding buttons to automatically open doors, installing wider doors).  Given all of these issues relating to navigating around the park, the very least the managers could do is provide wheelchairs for free conditional on providing a security deposit or leaving an ID card.  Other local museums provide wheelchairs for free, and a $35 initial payment is excessive in light of the $24 admission fee that is charged for entering the zoo.< /review>< GmapID>

We had a wonderful time and learned much. We spent most of our time on the new California Trail accessed via gondola ride. <Rating>5</Rating>< review>
Nice zoo. Most the enclosures are spacious. The animals were active. Lots of docents were available to answer questions. We saw several zoo keepers caring for animals and they were friendly, knowledgeable, and willing to answer questions. We went on an overcast partly rainy day in spring: the train, most the concessions, and the rides were not open due to weather, but we were able to park close in the parking lot and there were no crowds. Highly recommend riding the gondola up to let the kids play on the playground- great nature theame playground for all ages with amazing views and excellent California history on top. Overall, very good day exploring conservation and learning about animals which is why we went!<//review>

It didn't mention that you had to pay to stay at the park past the regular 5pm closing time. So we were told by 1 staff member that the zoo was indeed open until 8 but it was never said that they would lick is out at 5 and then make us re-enter. < Review>
I haven't been to a lot of zoos and wasn't expecting much, except a chance to see some young cousins.  (Humans I was spending time with there, not monkeys.)  I was pleasantly surprised by the zoo, though.  Particularly fascinating watching the social dynamics between the different kinds of primates -- although maybe I just got lucky.  Certainly a lot of animals were just lying around in the hot sun.   Also, it's nice to give kids a visceral sense that this diversity of animals is real.< /Review>

<review>I love going to the Oakland Zoo, they have lots of animals to see and fun things for the kids to to do. There's a train that takes you around a section of the property, a cable car system that takes you up and over the lions and giraffes to another section of the park with a great view of both Oakland and San Francisco cities from the cable cars.

They also have a new cable car system that takes you on top of the hill to a beautiful restaurant and lovely view of the two cities. The staff all around the zoo are always very friendly and seems to be very knowledgeable about the animals, you'll see them hanging out around some of the main area of the zoo to answer any questions about the animals or to give directions to the to the guests.

Overal, the Oakland Zoo is a wonderful  little treasure in the city of Oakland which attracts visitors from all around the world.

Have fun at the zoo!! I hope this helps.</review>< Pictures>

< rate>

< text>
The vegetation is lovely around the Zoo although it would be nice to have more trails to take various ways to different exhibits. The animals had well sized and varied enclosures  only problem was vegetation was lush enough to make some hard to find in exhibits.

The Gondola ride was highlight of trip and it will be nice to visit when paths and exhibits are open at the top. The best dining was at the top yet it was always crowded so hopefully they will add more seating, especially outside with the view. That was very limited. It would be a great setting for an evening event at the Zoo and it would be fun to see an adult type event utilizing the spectacular view of the Bay Area and San Francisco.

We were fortunate to have perfect weather. Just enough breeze and temperate weather to make it very comfortable. It might get hot in mid-summer since it's exposed in areas and away from the coast. It's a great place to spend an active day with family.</text>

<GmapID>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa<//GmapID></record></dataset><record>
< Text>
Good place for a family day trip. The main zoo part is fun to traverse because the trail goes up and down and through trees and brush. I felt like I was walking through Jurassic Park. It's nice and big with lots to see and some grassy areas to run around in or have a picnic lunch. There's a new part of the zoo that's only accessed by a gondola ride up the foothills. Once you're up there it's this huge deck that goes around the perimeter and you look down into the enclosures to see the wolves or whatnot. There's an area for the kids to play and climb on stuff.

The cons of visiting here though is that first off it's not nearly as aesthetic as the SF zoo. They've left it pretty overgrown and natural which isn't a bad thing per ces but it does feel a little out of control. Also, there were a lot of exhibits that were closed and empty. If they can't put an animal there then they should clear it for picnic benches or playgrounds. The bathrooms were a wreck! Dirty and a lot of non functional sinks/dispensers/etc. And lastly, there was literally 2 benches to sit down on to rest or just watch an animal up in the newer area and the whole area is pretty much in the sun. So as cool as the new area is, it was pretty miserable to visit when you couldn't sit down and rest for 5 minutes or get out of the sun< /Text>
<Rating>4</Rating>< Gmap_id>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /Gmap_id>

<text>Not so big, but big enough to spend a day (10am to 4pm).. Love the Tigers, Lions and Elephants there, Other interesting animals there are Giraffe, Camel, Alligators, Tortoise, Chimpanzee, Zebra, Small python, Kangaroo(by train), birds and more.. Free gondola rides, the small one goes over Tigers and Lions, by Camel, Giraffe and Elephants, the big one takes you to a restaurant and another area that is opening in summer 2018.. The kids rides are not free with the entrance tickets, costs ~$2 to $4 per ride. Train ride is $3.5 per person . OR I think you can pay extra $24 for all the rides. Parking extra $10.< /text>< response>

There are a lot of hills, so it's moderately strenuous to spend the day there.  Apart from the zoo (separate, but adjoining) is a small amusement park for younger kids. <userid>112734700573537482255</userid>< Name>
Pablo Rabasa</Name>
<date>1577558843333<//date><rating>5< /rating><Text>This is a terrific zoo! While it is not the San Diego zoo, it is far superior to the San Francisco Zoo. It has very natural large enclosures for the animals and seems to incorporate various aspects of the land. The addition of the gondola and the California wildlife exhibit at the top of the hill is amazing. I love how it seems as though the enclosures are really nothing more than an untouched  patch of native land including namesake Oak trees. My favorite animal is the jaguar, which my 18 month old daughter referred to as a kittykat when it was locked eyes with her six inches from the glass. I jokingly informed her that kittykat was looking at her like a snack. The highlight of the medium sized play area is the zipline. There is always a line of parents and kids waiting for there chance to send their kids flying down into a quintet of springs that stop the flyer less violently than other ziplines I have seen and ridden. Great selection of animals with Africa making the most prolific appearance. Overall it is an awesome zoo and I highly recommend it.< /Text>< Pics>
None<//Pics>
