</dataset><record>
<Date>1578036038343< /Date><rating>3< /rating><Text>Mismanaged and disorganized, but the kids don't care! Also, member tips included!

I'll start by saying we are members of the OZ, and have been for years. We believe in the mission and the kids love it - zoo lights, the gondola, the new California experience, the rides, and every single animal habitat... truly, they LOVE IT.

Here's the but, and this hopefully is constructive... It is poorly managed. You can tell this is a culture thing. It comes from the top down. Keep in mind that the members and visitors really only see and interact with the service staff. Not the zoo keepers, not the management, but the people running the show. It is abundantly clear that they are just there to push a button or advance a line or sling a chicken tender. They are not there to be helpful or usually even polite. In fact, most of them are on their phones and, if they even look at you, it looks as if their very souls are being crushed if you deign to ask where the restroom is. Crushed.

The volunteers, on the other hand, are usually the opposite and go out of their way to provide info, chat up your kids, or just make sure you're enjoying yourself. Strangely, not paid.

Anyway, as promised, here is the local/member tips part: if you don't have kids in tow, do whatever you like, unencumbered and free to enjoy without a million bathroom and snack breaks! If, like most of us, you have at least one young child in tow, lucky you! Seeing this world through the eyes of a child is pure magic, so:
1. Arrive by 10am. Forget nap. Park in the upper lot nearest the main entrance. If you arrive past 10am on a weekend there's a good chance you're parking in the lower lot of having to walk some insane distance up a crazy hill.
2. Bring a stroller with storage space or a wagon, snacks, plenty of water/juice boxes (for bribery), and a full meal. Also a blanket.
3. It's usually good weather in the hills, so bring layers, but plan to be warmer than colder. Sunglasses, hats, and sunscreen help a lot.
4. They recently changed the parking paradigm so now you have to collect a ticket and pay for parking at admission, which is truly the DUMBEST THING EVER. Until they change it back, park in the upper lot and as close to the rides as possible. This is important.
5. Dress said children in sturdy, comfy shoes that will not fall off their feet. See gondolas, roller coaster, running, frog pond, and any other number of fun things where shoes go missing.
6. Do not, under any circumstances, go to Tuskers, the restaurant. Not only is it crazy overpriced, it also takes exactly one elephant's life span to get your food. Unfortunately, they have excellent french fries, so you will be tempted. See #2.
7. Best exhibits: the California Experience (new high speed gondola up to the highest point of the zoo), the lions (best view of those guys from the original gondola ride near the train tracks), the lower Children's playground and frog pond/alligator exhibit, and the amphibian and reptile house. We also love the bat house but that's not for everyone!
8. Best rides: the train, of course, but the line is long so be prepared to wait and have some fun riddle or something for the kiddos to do whilst waiting, otherwise you're just in for a lot of swinging from the corral railings. The carousel is well done and the tiger roller coaster is scary-fun, in a mostly good way. The littlest ones will like the car "driving" ride and the carousel, the Jeep ride and perhaps the airplanes. Tickets for rides are the best deal at $24 for 16 booklet. Otherwise they're $1.75 each.
9. End your day at the rides, bribe everyone with a cotton candy or ice cream to get them to leave, and then voila! You're right near your car and the exit!
10. Become a member. We kvetch, but the money is immediately made up in just one family outing, and it goes to a really good cause!

If they would just revamp the management, put a little more pep in everyone's step, and sweep and paint the place so it doesn't look so shabby and run down, then we'd be in business. Dare I say we might even get 4 or more stars.</Text><user_id>106247273822469948102</user_id><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Gmap_id>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa</Gmap_id>

<UserId.>102067358574939362813</UserId.>< Text>
Visited with my then 6 year old son mid-week, on a day threatening rain so we had the place pretty much to ourselves.

Sat on a bench for a while watching a chimpanzee idle his way through a Seventeen magazine, glancing up every page or two to see what his (her) mates were up to.

Hard to convey how electrifying it was to experience the presence of this animal that seemed just a few notches away from humanity.  Stayed with me for days.</Text>

<Text>As Zoos go, this is one of the nicer zoos. Habitats seem friendlier to the occupants. It is set up as, somewhat, meandering trails. Thus, you are not just walking from one enclosure to another. Kathryn L<//user_name>
<Time>1487044799442</Time><rate>4<//rate>< text>
I went to the Oakland zoo last Friday with my daughter‚Äôs class for a field trip. The trip was well planned out. At the zoo they have classrooms for all of the guided tours. Our teacher/tour guide was supper friendly and had lots of information to give out.

This is my first time going to the zoo and I was surprised to see how nice the zoo was.  It is a large zoo and the animals looked happy for the most part. The best part of the zoo was seeing all of the animals out and about. We saw the lions, elephants, giraffes and flamingos just to name a few. (Going early is probably the best time).

After the tour the kids were able to go back to the classroom and have lunch. They also have a nice courtyard for the kids to eat at. The day we went it had just rained, so we were not able to enjoy the outside area.
Next to classroom was a whole area set up for the kids to run and play. I loved how you could explore and find new areas of the zoo. The kids had a great time seeing the bug exhibit and crocodiles. I also liked that the exhibits were scattered throughout the park and exploring with the kids was so much fun.

My group had time to pet the animals which was a nice touch. I wish I had more time to explore the zoo, but the bus was ready to pick us up and go back to school.</text>

< userid>
116206320499878209130<//userid>
<Name>aaron prather< /Name><pictures>None< /pictures><text>I've lived in the Bay Area since 1990. I just visited the Oakland Zoo for the first time this year. My friends and I arrived before the gates opened and joined a line. It's a little, ok a lot, crazy at the gates before they open. Lots of confusion, coupled with excitement. Screaming kids, yelling parents, the usual. Once the gates open, it's a free for all. Everyone is pushing and running. I'm convinced the adults misbehave more than adults.
Once inside, we made our way to the new gondolas. We were literally the first ones there and ended up waiting a few more minutes for the attraction to open. No worries.
The gondolas were comfortable and clean. The boarding and exiting process were seamless. (even for a wheelchair in my party)
The views from the gondolas are phenomenal. The higher you go, the more of the Bay Area you see. The gentle breeze was a welcomed bonus.
The food court was a pleasant surprise. Personally, I don't think the prices were too high. The food was actually delicious. Each of us got something different and none of us were disappointed.
We enjoyed all of the animals and exhibits. I'm glad we went early. The park gets really crowded. It really warms up too. I thought I was going to pass out while visiting the camels. Can't wait to go back now that the new exhibits are open.</text>< Date>
1537405227711</Date>

<review>Awesome!!!! One of the BEST zoos I've ever been too! The first, in fact. I used to live in Oakland and conveniently close to the zoo. Even now in Danville, a town Contra Costa County, but along the border of Alameda County, I still live close, for it is on the other side of San Ramon. I've always loved that zoo ever since I was little and I still love it now. Eleven years ago, I also attended a zoo camp program and LOVED IT!!!!

I strongly recommended this zoo to everyone - especially those that live in the East Bay. I also recommend this zoo to scientists, like myself, those that want the access to animals they don't usually get to encounter, those that love nature and being outdoors, and all Lion King fans, such as me!!

Every time I've been to the Oakland Zoo, the place has also reminded me of the animal/nature films I grew up with such as Dumbo, The Jungle Book, and of course, The Lion King. I've been there many times with friends and I'm strongly hoping to get a job there someday.

I've had so much experience with the Oakland Zoo and have loved it! Everyone there is treated like friends and family. It is a perfect place for others to spend time at and socialize, and also to hold events.

If you need time to spend with lions, tigers, elephants, bears or other animals you don't get to be with everyday, come to the Oakland Zoo and see how awesome that zoo really is!<//review><Response>{'time': 1599151439106, 'text': "Thank you so much for the nice review Peter. <rate>5<//rate>< GmapID>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa<//GmapID>
< Review>
Born an raised in Oakland, always had a good time. We got the membership for our family, why take the kids to the park when you can go to the zoo any day! The animals look healthy, it's well kept, and plenty to see. They are expanding the zoo to add a few more animals which is great. The lift to the cafe up top is free, also has a great view of Oakland. I've been taking my daughter here since she was born and she pretty much memorized the entire park. Shes never bored of it. Theres always something new to learn or talk about. Fun for the entire family. If you dont enjoy walking especially uphill, then that's a shame. It's great exercise for the kids and for yourself. The amusement park on the side of the zoo is fun for the kids too, the only ride I didn't like is the tiger roller coaster. I took my daughter on it recently for the first time. Seemed pretty dangerous because it didn't really secure her in place. If I wasn't in the ride with her, holding her head, she definitely would have hurt herself. Possibly banging her head into the ride. Other than that the other rides are safe and in great order.</Review>

We got directed to the farthest part of the park. We didn't get any options of where to park which might be harder for families who have strollers or have family memebers who are disabled. Walking on grass isn't easy for you to push your stroller. Once coming on from the bottom entrance we loved every spot from the insects to tortoises. The kids love exploring the park and seeing these animals through very safe displays. We didn't have the chance ro ride the train but it looked really fun if we have another chance down the road.the newest part of the park, which you have to take the newest gondola, was great! The gondola goes up high and smoothly as long as you stay seated and don't move a lot. Each gondola can hold up to 6 adults which is great for families who have kids and many adults. Once to the top the bison were nice. The main attraction were the grizzly bears which you could see them from all angles and they could have privacy, have a swim to cool off and enjoy a simple swim. The cages up here were well thought out and they seem tranquil.when we got back down we went through the safari section of the park. When we got to the lion exhibit we could not see them but we definitely could hear them. When we got to elephant part one of the elephants seems depressed but I don't know why. I hope the people at the zoo see this and help it. At the very end we walked the whole park and left 40 minutes after closing time but we lived the park. If you go on a beautiful sunny day you can see the north part of the bay easily as we did. Would I go back? <text>What a fun place! I'm used to going to the San Diego zoo (which is one of the best in the world!), so I honestly went not expecting much. We love the Oakland Zoo and happily renewed our family membership a month ago. Sure the camel "habitat" is just a grassy hillside with a fence around it. Sure the alligators occasionally get loose (we're assured they're overfed and not dangerous, lol). Sure the Sky Ride literally caught fire last time we were there. Whatever. < Gmap_id>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa<//Gmap_id>
< Review>
This zoo keeps getting better and better, and it's in a beautiful setting in the oakland hills.
Zoo personnel around the grounds are available for questions about the animals.
This is one of very few zoos that has African elephants instead of Asian.  It takes 20 keepers to care for the 4 elephants.
You can visit bars, bugs, reptiles and alligators in the children's zoo and of course , owt the goats.
Newer native animal section at the top of the hill.  Gondolas take you up to the top of the hill to a wheelchair accessible walkway thru native California animal enclosures including Grizzlies, condors, mountain lions and gray wolves.
Get to the zoo when it opens, there's a lot to see and parking fills up fast</Review>

<Response>None< /Response><name>B Martin</name><pictures>None< /pictures><user_id>105811020333096380108</user_id>< Review>
Well worth a visit. However, call in advance if you are planning to see the elephants being fed. When we visited with our grandchild, the elephant exhibit was closed with heavy equipment sitting around. However, all the large animals are being fed in the morning shortly after opening. It was interesting watching the giraffe and camels munching on branches that seemed inedible. We especially enjoyed the jaguar, mountain lion, and grizzly bear exhibits (reached by gondola). The black bear exhibit was great. We had a front row seat watching a large bear floating on its back with it's paws up out of the water only three or four feet away through a glass partition.<//Review>

< time>
1547350265354</time>
</record></dataset><record>
< Review>
For my list, I've created a bucket list of places to go. And they've been to all the zoos beside Oakland zoo. In December, one of my friends went to the Oakland Zoo with her 2 year old and family. She cognizant that Oakland zoo is not huge and not that many animals to see.  Although her reviews were stuck in my heard, I still sought to see for myself.
Entrance- At the zoo parking entrance, you have to pay $10. There were signs posted on the windows of the entrance, credit card system temporarily down and cash accepted. I pretended as if we didn't read the instruction and gave my credit card. They guy said you don't have cash. I replied, no. Then he swiped my card. I guess to speed up at the entrance, they posted those signs.

We purchased the tickets at the  zoo entrance and I kept saying to myself that should have purchased the groupon deal. It was expensive, $19 per adult without tax and for 2 year and up they charge.  I think best time to come to the zoo is in the morning. We reached the zoo at 10.30am and the parking lot was almost full. At the entrance, make sure to grab the map so you don't miss out anything. Once you enter the zoo you'll see the gift shop on your right and the flamingos directly in front of you. Near the gift shop are the restrooms and on the left is the restaurant where we ate.  The gift shop is small but remarkable,  great educational toys, t-shirts, hats, sunblock, puzzles and etc.

Outside the zoo is the Outback Express Adventure Train.  They have a train ride for adults and children that go around the zoo. Every time my daughter see the train, we have to ride. And she loved it. Our conductor did not give much information.
After paying the zoo entrance, we paid additional for the train ride. I felt everything was adding up very fast.

Wear comfortable shoes because there are steep hills in different portions of the zoo.
For the sky ride, you have to pay $ 3per person. I have 9 months old and they charged $3 for the baby. You can see most of the animals through the sky ride and it was totally worth it. I loved the newly opened Gondola ride. It had a beautiful view of the bay area. We saw elephants, giraffes, zebra, turtle, lemur, lion, buffalo, tiger and etc.

Overall, this was a great zoo and I would definitely come back when the new area is opened.< /Review>

< Review>
I love this Zoo! Very informative and the staff is very eager to answer your questions.  I had asked about a cat that I saw with a bib on and this young lady with the goats and sheep answered all my questions.  I wish I had gotten her name,  she was very nice.

My recommendation is to just go!  Go when they open for the best parking and a little more animal activity,  excerpt the big cats. Lol.   Oh, and bring your lunch it's pretty pricey to eat there..</Review>

<Text>We love Oakland Zoo.  They work hard to provide human enclosures and treatment for the animals.  Some other posters mentioned trash in the enclosures.  They give the animals different things for enrichment.  What looks like trash is actually for the benefits of the animals to keep them stimulated and healthy.

They also have a fun amusement area outside of the zoo.  You can access those rides without paying for entrance.  My son loves the train.  It takes you to the Australian Outback which has emus, wallaroos and a fantastic view of the bay.

Their annual Walk in the Wild fundraising event is awesome.  We went last year and can't wait to go this year.  It's so much fun.</Text><Time>1460265264995</Time><pics>None</pics></record>

< userid>
105332917839725645173</userid>
<rating>4</rating><Text>The zoo is a pretty good size for an afternoon trip with kids. It takes about 3 hours to walk around the zoo to see all animals. Visitors are welcome to bring their own food to picnic there as well as have meals there is their various restaurants.
We got a chance to see many animals in action but it's a pity that the distance is too far for phone cameras.

There are a few things to note here though.
1. Kids need admission fee after 2. Unlike SF zoo, which offers kids free until they're 3.
2. Parking fee is $9 per car.
3. They do take 'passport' discount. =D
4. All the rides inside are extra. Sky ride is $3 per person and it's a around 20 minutes ride and you got a good view of the zoo. The play ground area is separated from the zoo and you can enter the area without zoo admission. Most rides there cost $1.5 and $3.

One thing about here is that I wish their staff can be more properly trained. The staff at entrance didn't even greet us and give us a map. Moreover, the staff at various exits didn't even bother to hold door for us even we have strollers, which is quite rude. I take one star off due to this.</Text>< username>
Jack Chu</username>

106894318371508656086</user>
<gmap_id>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /gmap_id><Pics>None< /Pics>< review>
Go early as the lines can get long.
If it's your first time, you'll need 3-4 hours to see the whole thing. Our 2 year old was done in about 3.

Almost all the animals were out and about but the bears were fun to watch. The zoo staff brought the 4 grizzlies close, to feed them fruits and play with them. The black bear cubs were having a blast amongst themselves, climbing on trees and jumping in the water. Don't miss taking the gondola ride to go see them at the California Trail section. Plus the view from the top is a bonus!!</review>

Mindy M< /name>
<Date>1517974343529<//Date><rate>4<//rate>< Text>
This zoo has most of the animals you expect and hope to see at a zoo, the enclosures are decent sized, and the animals seem to be well cared for. The bathrooms are dated. The rides expensive, so we skip them. I wish there were more zoo staff around to talk to about the animals. And it's sometimes hard to see the animals due to the design of the pens.. which is probably best for the animals, but frustrating for children. Just be prepared for a hike, this zoo is on a hill and is a hike. I personally leave the stroller and take a carrier for my littles.</Text>

<userid>117587702328815101336<//userid>< name>
Duncan Crowley< /name>
<time>1532898413437</time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< Text>
A few weeks ago I might have given this zoo only 3 stars because the lower part of the zoo is not extraordinary and it is quite crowded with loud young children. As you can imagine, this doesn't make me or the animals particularly happy. What redeemed all of those things for me was the new zoo expansion, known as the California trail. The area is accessible by a short gondola ride with the greatest view of the entire Bay. The gondola line was somewhat long when we rode up but was fast moving, and it was practically nonexistant when we rode down. The animals in this upper level were all CA animals, either historically (like the wolf and jaguar) or currently. The exhibits for all these animals were new and spacious, expanding the zoo's land area to nearly that of the great San Diego Zoo. I will say this zoo still pales in comparison to the one in San Diego, but is certainly the now best in the whole Bay area, and certainly more than worth the $20 entry fee. If you discounted this zoo before the expansion, I'd recommend giving it a second chance because the view on the California trail is more than worth the entry fee.<//Text>
<pics>None<//pics><response>None</response>< GmapID>

<review>Didn't realize Oakland had a zoo. It is a very nice zoo. The enclosures seem to be properly sized for the animals which is a nice change from most zoos. The 1 star off is because this zoo is expensive ($10 to enter the park the zoo is in, $22 for zoo admission). Lots of costly add ons (though not required). However, a new board walk section being built with a free gondola ride stands to be a great addition.

This is a good place to visit if you are looking for a different side of Oakland<//review><Date>1529802282412<//Date>< GmapID>

< Text>
I had a bad experience at the Oakland Zoo today. My two sons 5 & 8 were looking forward to riding the plane ride that they always ride when they come to the zoo, but this time the ride operator told my son that he couldn't ride because he was too tall. I told her that I had just measured him next to their height requirement sign, and he was definitely under the max height limit which was 58 inches. The ride operator says "he is shorter than 58 inches, but we changed the height limit to 54 inches", I said if you changed it, u should of changed it on the signs, my son has been waiting excitedly in line to get on this ride. The ride operator acted like she didn't care that the sign said 58 inches, so I had the supervisor come down. The supervisor says, even if we go off the posted 58 inches sign, he is still taller, so I put him next to the sign & showed him my son was shorter than 58 inches, and the supervisor like no sorry he can't ride. He had the nerve to tell me that my son's hair counts as height (because my son has dreads that sit up on his head like a high top) so I put his hair in a ponytail to show he wasn't as tall, but he didn't care. I felt like they were intentionally trying to was upset me, yht supervisor saw he was wrong, but wasn't man enough to admit it, and apologize and let my son ride the ride. My son was so excited about going to the zoo, and he was enjoying himself, untill we got to the ride area, he was so disappointed. I will never go there again.< /Text>

< Text>
The size of the Oakland Zoo is perfect for toddlers and children under the age of 10.¬†Having visited both the San Diego Safari Park and the Omaha Zoo with open range enclosures, this small zoo managed to create some open space for the large animals like the giraffes, lions, tigers and elephants rather than enclose them entirely in a cage.¬†¬†¬†On a hot day, the shaded seats in the outdoor theatre can serve as a sitting area to rest or have lunch when there‚Äôs no show in progress.¬†¬†For those with children, the membership plans can be a good deal with free admission most days of the year.< /Text>

<Pictures>None< /Pictures><rate>3</rate><Review>Don't get me wrong, it is fairly good zoo, but I felt like I wanted to see more. First things first. It is conveniently located just one block from highway and entrance is easily accessible regardless where you park. Admission price per adult is $17 which is not bad, but you actually have to pay more. Read until the end.

A few animals that I have seen are baboon, tigers, tortoise, elephants, camels, hyena, giraffes, wallaroo, otters, goats, etc. I have seen all these animals before and wanted to see more birds (only one parrot type, really?).

Some exhibits where closed and I would love to see anaconda, but I couldn't due to remodeling. Definitely there is lack of exotic insects.

The unexpected part was is the way of seeing wallaroo. It is only accessible with the small train and there is additional price of $3 per person for that. I thought that I am paying $17 to see animals.

Overall, it was OK experience, but I am not coming back. Work harder, Oakland Zoo< /Review>< UserId.>

<review>It's closer than the SF Zoo for people in the East Bay. That's about all that's really good about it. A lot of animals are hard to see for smaller kids, and often unnecessarily so, e.g., by painting a glass wall over. The staff is rarely helpful, most of the times they are more on the rude side. It's pricey and the rides are annoying. The kids always want to go to the rides instead of visiting the animals. It's my least favorite zoo but it's close enough to be convenient for a short morning entertainment, so I got a membership. After 11:30 AM it gets too full anyways.</review>< pics>

The zoo is a great place to spend a day with the kids.The new part of the zoo is fantastic.If you are afraid of heights you might not get to see the new part as the only way to it is by tram.The size of the zoo has doubled in size so there will be a lot of walking.The wolves are awsome to see.There is a male and a female.Just fyi the prices have gone up quite a bit also from tickets to get in to the food prices.On the weekends parking is horrible and traffic to get in even worse.All in all the Oakland Zoo is a fun place to go with or without kids.< /Text>

< user>
105529300056545653455<//user>
<name>royalsamurai1<//name><Date>1490990651455</Date>< Rating>
4</Rating>
< review>
You would think by having the San Francisco Zoo, it would be enough, but we have another zoo across the bay, which in size, is not as enormous as San Francisco's but I think is just as enjoyable.

It offers residents in the Eastbay easy access for that "zoo fix" in most of us! ¬†I like the easy access from the freeway (Highway 580) and the large parking lot which is in front of the zoo.

With this zoo, you are walking up and down small hills to view the numerous animals but "my favorite part of the zoo has to be the sky-ride." ¬†I believe the San Diego Zoo is the only other zoo in California that is equipped with a "tram-like" ride over the zoo, but this one is a "ski-lift" type of ride, which I think is one of a kind.

The lift takes you over the lion's den and giraffe prairie and gives you a whole new perspective from above!

Another favorite attraction of mine is the meerkat exhibit where in the wild these animals live in large "clans" and to me is just entertaining to watch.</review>

<review>A great place to take the kids to see a wide variety of animals.  This zoo has done a lot over the years to greatly increase the size of the animal enclosures.  You'll see African elephants, tigers, meerkats, zebras, lions, giraffes, camels, bison, a wide variety of birds, sun bears, baboons, monkeys, etc.  Included in the zoo is a children's zoo featuring repitles (including alligators), amphibians, various bugs & insects, fruit bats, lemurs, and more.  A separate train ride just outside the zoo gates will take you through an Outback with some Australian animals wander about.</review>< Pics>

Was extremely difficult for a wheelchair person to get around without help. Animal collection was fair. Loved the Meercat exhibit because you could see them fairly upclose. They were certainly well fed!!! Felt some of the cages were too small and unkempt, poorly constructed, and the visibility to the animals was poor as well. All in all I would rate it a 5 out of 10. Sorry, but I won't be planning a return trip anytime soon.<//review>

<Review>We love the zoo! It focuses on safari and jungle animals and is currently missing california animals, but there is a california animal exhibit under construction. It's got lots of seating around the major habitats, like the elephants and monkeys. And it's got a great kids zoo. There are big animal statues to climb on all over and there is a petting zoo where the kids can pet/brush goats. The only downside is it's built on a hill, but that means you get a good workout! There is a small attached amusement park with rides you can pay for. There's also a train that goes around the zoo and a skylift that flies over it, though both of those cost money too. There are two train crossings, which my toddler loves! Its a great zoo and open all year round.</Review>< pics>

We had so much fun. There isn't a lot of food options but we were able to bring some snacks and water bottles in. Wasn't crazy busy even on a weekend, but that's probably because you had to reserve your time for going. All the staff seemed friendly and helpful. Did get a little lost a few times but that may be user issues.<//review>

(Translated by Google) Although it is a corona wreck, I visited in February 2021 when it was reopened due to a lot of efforts to ensure safety.

You can ride a gondola, and in normal times there are merry-go-rounds and various children's attractions, so it's perfect for playing with children.

Not all elephants are in San Francisco Zoo!

< review>
(Translated by Google) Good city zoo and with enough parking spaces. The zoo is reasonably priced for a 1 round zoo. It is under development and the stays are good, but could be better. The lions were well housed and the elephants had some space. It is a pity that the voilieres have a lot of thread, but for the small children it is a great educational zoo. The alligators and bats are beautiful. Close to and for a European once not in a blood hot hall.

(Original)
Goede stadsdierentuin en met voldoende parkeerplaatsen. De dierentuin is redelijk aan de prijs voor een 1 rondje dierentuin. Het is in ontwikkeling en de verblijven zijn goed, maar kan beter. De leeuwen waren goed gehuisvest en de olifanten hadden wat ruimte. Jammer dat de voilieres veel draad hebben, maar voor de kleine kinderen is het een prima educatieve zoo. Wel mooi zijn de alligators en vleermuizen. Dichtbij en voor een Europeaan een keer niet in een bloed hete hal.</review>

(Translated by Google) Very good zoo, more diversity of species is needed, the existing ones are very well cared for and some facilities are large. The Sun Bear is not common in zoos, the gondolas are a super plus, the view is truly spectacular, it is included, although 22 dollars per adult the entrance is expensive in my opinion. In the summer of 2018 there will be new attractions, such as the California Conservation Habitarium, facilities for Grizzly Bear, Condor Jaguars, Cougars, among others.
Current installations such as that of the Muntiac are on a steep slope, so they are never seen. Enjoy it.
